ys and two [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The original doorway has a [[chamfer]]ed surround, composite [[jamb]]s and a deep [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]], and there is a 19th-century doorway with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] jambs and lintel.  The main window is chamfered and [[mullion]]ed with eight lights.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227396|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Lower Purprice<br/><small>{{coord|53.76559|-2.01446|type:landmark|name=Lower Purprice}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1675|Late 17th century}}\n|A stone house that has a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s, kneelers, and diamond-shaped [[finial]]s.  There are two storeys and two [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The porch is gabled with a finial, and has an arched doorway with a [[chamfer]]ed surround, and a window above.  The windows are chamfered and [[mullion]]ed, and in the right return is a three-light window with arched lights, sunken [[spandrel]]s and [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] mullions.{{sfnp|Historic England|1265382|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Nook Farmhouse and barn<br/><small>{{coord|53.74746|-1.99070|type:landmark|name=Nook Farmhouse}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1675|Late 17th century}}\n|The oldest part is a cottage, to which the farmhouse was added in the 18th century, and a barn at the other end in the 19th century.  The building is in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and a stone slate roof.  The windows are [[mullion]]ed, and the house has two doorways, one with tie-stone [[jamb]]s, the other with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s.  In the barn is a semicircular-arched cart entry flanked by doorways.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227154|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Purprice Farmhouse<br/><small>{{coord|53.76559|-2.01459|type:landmark|name=Purprice  Farmhou