 Town Farm Cottages<br/><small>{{coord|53.75110|-2.00139|type:landmark|name=Old Town Farm Cottages}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1750|Mid 18th century}}\n|A pair of stone cottages with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and a stone slate roof.  There are two storeys, and each cottage has one [[bay (architecture)|bay]], a doorway with a [[chamfer]]ed surround, composite [[jamb]]s, and a quoined [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]], and the windows are [[mullion]]ed.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227340|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Building south of Pecket Well Mill Shed<br/><small>{{coord|53.76323|-2.00560|type:landmark|name=Building south of Pecket Well Mill Shed}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1750|Mid 18th century}}\n|A pair of mirror-image stone cottages that have a stone slate roof with [[gable]]s and kneelers.  There are two storeys and two [[bay (architecture)|bays]]  The windows are [[chamfer]]ed and [[mullion]]ed, and the doorways have chamfered surrounds and [[quoin (architecture)|quoined]] [[lintel (architecture)|lintels]]; the right doorway is blocked.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227148|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Top O'th Hill<br/><small>{{coord|53.74925|-1.99424|type:landmark|name=Top O'th Hill}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1825|Early 19th century}}\n|A pair of cottages was added to the original cottage in the 19th century and it has been combined into a single dwelling.  It is in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], and stone slate roofs with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  The original cottage has one storey, one [[bay (architecture)|bay]], and a doorway with a [[chamfer]]ed surround, tie-stone [[jamb]]s, and a quoined [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]].  The later cottages have two storeys and two bays, and the windows in both parts are [[mullion]]ed.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227306|