]] [[gable]]s with kneelers.  There are two storeys and three [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The windows are [[chamfer]]ed and [[mullion]]ed with three lights, the middle light taller.  Each bay has a doorway with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s.{{sfnp|Historic England|1265384|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|9, 11 and 12 Black Hill Bottom<br/><small>{{coord|53.76240|-2.00566|type:landmark|name=9, 11 and 12 Black Hill Bottom}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1800|18th to early 19th century}}\n|A group of stone cottages with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], and stone slate roofs with kneelers.  There are two storeys and attics, and two [[bay (architecture)|bays]] on the west front.  The windows are [[mullion]]ed, some doorways have tie-stone [[jamb]]s, and others have [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] jambs.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227308|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Higher Crimsworth<br/><small>{{coord|53.76402|-2.00982|type:landmark|name=Higher Crimsworth}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1800|Late 18th to early 19th century}}\n|A row of [[back to back house|back to back]] cottages converted into two dwellings.  They are in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s.  The doorways have tie-stone [[jamb]]s, and the windows are [[mullion]]ed.{{sfnp|Historic England|1226986|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|New Bridge<br/><small>{{coord|53.75800|-2.01918|type:landmark|name=New Bridge}}</small>\n|[[File:New Bridge, Midgehole.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1800|18th to early 19th century}}\n|The bridge carries a road over Hebden Water.  It is in stone, and consists of a single segmental arch.  The bridge has a [[keystone (architecture)|keystone]], a band, a [[parapet]] and [[coping (architecture)|copings]].{{sfnp|