 1830}}\n|A row of three stone cottages, one of which was once a [[forge|smithy]].  They have been combined into a single house, and have [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and a stone slate roof.  There are two storeys and three [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The doorways have tie-stone [[jamb]]s, and the windows are [[mullion]]ed.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227388|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Pinfold<br/><small>{{coord|53.76221|-2.00516|type:landmark|name=Pinfold}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1830|c. 1830}}\n|The [[animal pound|pinfold]] is adjacent to Keighley Road and is in stone.  It contains [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], the wall facing the road is [[embattled]], and the entrance is in the north wall.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227143|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Crimsworth Methodist Church<br/><small>{{coord|53.76319|-2.00532|type:landmark|name=Crimsworth Methodist Church}}</small>\n|[[File:Former Crimsworth Methodist Church - geograph.org.uk - 1472319.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1834\n|The chapel is in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and a stone slate roof.  There are two storeys, and the front has three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], and a [[pediment]]ed [[gable]] with an inscription in the [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]].  In the centre is a doorway with [[pilaster]]s, and a [[cornice]].  There are four bays on the sides, and the windows on the front and sides have semicircular-arched heads, [[impost (architecture)|impost]] blocks, and [[keystone (architecture)|keystones]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1227145|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|1 and 2 Chiserley Hall and archway<br/><small>{{coord|53.75006|-1.99802|type:landmark|name=1 and 2 Chiserley Hall and archway}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1835|Early to mid 19th century}}\n|A pair of stone cottages with a stone slate roof.  