ad, Wadsworth - geograph.org.uk - 1241729.jpg|60px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1835|Early to mid 19th century}}\n|The guide post is on the west side of the A6033 road.  It is an upright stone with inscriptions on two faces, consisting of \"OLD ROAD\", pointing hands, and the directions to [[Haworth]], [[Keighley]] and [[Hebden Bridge]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1265571|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Guide post at junction of Akroyd Lane with Keighley Road<br/><small>{{coord|53.76069|-2.00678|type:landmark|name=Guide post at junction with A6033}}</small>\n|[[File:Guide stone, Keighley Road, Wadsworth - geograph.org.uk - 1239000.jpg|70px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1835|Early to mid 19th century}}\n|The guide post standing at a road junction is an upright stone with two inscribed faces.  It is inscribed with \" PARISH OF WADSWORTH \" and pointing hands indicating the directions to [[Old Town, West Yorkshire|Old Town]], [[Hebden Bridge]], [[Midgley]], [[Todmorden]], [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], [[Haworth]], [[Keighley]], and [[Oxenhope]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1265412|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Barn south of 2 Chiserley Hall<br/><small>{{coord|53.74989|-1.99802|type:landmark|name=Barn south of 2 Chiserley Hall}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1837\n|The barn is in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], and a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  It contains an elliptical-arched cart entry with [[rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] [[voussoir]]s flanked by doorways, and in the right return is an owl hole and a dated inscription.{{sfnp|Historic England|1265418|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Barn east of Ibbot Royd Farmhouse<br/><small>{{coord|53.74802|-1.99931|type:landmark|name=Barn east of Ibbot Royd Farmhouse}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1838\n|A stone barn that has a stone slate roof with a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]] and kneelers.  It contains an elliptical-arched cart entry, above it is a [[Venetian window]] with an [[impost (architecture)|impost]], a false keystone and a dated [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]], and to the sides are doorways with tie-stone [[jamb]]s and small windows.  In the right gable end are arrow slit vents, and an owl hole in the apex.{{sfnp|Historic England|1235131|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Pecket Well Mill<br/><small>{{coord|53.76357|-2.00571|type:landmark|name=Pecket Well Mill}}</small>\n|[[File:Pecket Well Mill, Wadsworth - geograph.org.uk - 1241679.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1840|c. 1840}}\n|A former [[fustian]] weaving mill that has been converted into flats.  The buildings are in stone and consist of the mill, a weaving shed, an engine room, and a chimney.  The mill has [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], a [[slate]] roof, three storeys, a symmetrical front of three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], and sides of nine bays.  The doorway has [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s and a [[cornice]] on [[corbel|consoles]], and there are two taking-in bays.  The chimney is circular and tapering, the engine house has a semicircular-arched window and a [[hipped roof]], and the shed has a semicircular-arched entry, a hoist, and seven circular holes.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=316|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1227147|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Barn and cottage south-east of Plumpton Farmhouse<br/><small>{{coord|53.76519|-2.00113|type:landmark|name=Barn and cottage south-east of Plumpton Farmhouse}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1843\n|A [[housebarn|laithe house]] in stone that has a [[slate]] roof with a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]].  The cottage has two storeys, one [[bay (architecture)|bay]], and an outshut.  It contains [[mullion]]ed windows and a doorway in the outshut.  The barn is higher and has a symmetrical front consisting of a central elliptical-arched cart entry with a [[keystone (architecture)|keystone]], above it is a [[Venetian window]] with a false keystone and a dated [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]], and to the sides are doorways and small windows.  In the left gable end are arrow slit vents, and an [[oculus]] in the apex.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227309|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Guide post at junction with Akroyd Lane and Patrock Lane<br/><small>{{coord|53.75400|-2.00471|type:landmark|name=Guide post at junction with Akroyd Lane and Patrock Lane}}</small>\n|[[File:Guide Stone, Old Town Mill Lane.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1850|Mid 19th century}}\n|The guide post is a horizontal stone at a road junction, engraved with a pointing hand and \"OLD TOWN\".{{sfnp|Historic England|1265495|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Guide post at junction with Walker Lane<br/><small>{{coord|53.75107|-2.00055|type:landmark|name=Guide post at junction with Walker Lane}}</small>\n|[[File:Guide Stone, Walker Lane.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1850|Mid 19th century}}\n|The guide post is a stone set into a [[dry stone]] wall at a road junction.  It is engraved with a pointing hand and \"OLD TOWN\".{{sfnp|Historic England|1227290|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Milestone north of junction with Midgehole Road<br/><small>{{coord|53.75328|-2.00861|type:landmark|name=Milestone north of junction with Midgehole Road}}</small>\n|[[File:Milestone, Keighley Road.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1850|Mid 19th century}}\n|The milestone is on the east side of Keighley road (A6033 road).  It is in [[cast iron]], it has a triangular plan and a sloping top.  The milestone is inscribed with the distances to [[Hebden Bridge]] and [[Keighley]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1227142|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Old Town Mill<br/><small>{{coord|53.75213|-2.00348|type:landmark|name=Old Town Mill}}</small>\n|[[File:Old Town Mill, Chiserley.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1851\n|The former [[worsted]] mill, which was extended in 1881 and 1889, and has since been used for other purposes, is in [[gritstone]] with roofs of [[slate]] and corrugated iron.  The mill consists of the former spinning mill, a warehouse, boiler and engine rooms, a chimney and sheds.  The original mill has two storeys and an attic, with sides of ten and seven [[bay (architecture)|bays]], a [[belt course|sill band]], a [[modillion]] [[eaves]] [[cornice]] and [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s with kneelers.  The boiler house has a single bay and a [[hipped roof]], the chimney stack is cylindrical, the warehouse has four storeys and attic and is ten bays long, and there is a stair tower with a pyramidal roof.{{sfnp|Historic England|1422136|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|[[Wainsgate Baptist Church]] and Sunday School<br/><small>{{coord|53.75555|-2.00415|type:landmark|name=Wainsgate Baptist Church and Sunday School}}</small>\n|[[File:Wainsgate Chapel - geograph.org.uk - 1496960.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1859\n|The chapel and Sunday school are in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]] and [[slate]] roofs.  The chapel has two storeys and a symmetrical front of three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], with a [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] [[eaves]] [[cornice]], and a [[pediment]]ed [[gable]].  The central doorway has panelled [[pilaster]]s, a [[fanlight]], [[spandrel]]s, a moulded cornice, and a date plaque above.  There are four bays on the sides, and the windows are [[archivolt]]-arched with [[architrave]]s and [[keystone (architecture)|keystones]].  The school at the rear has two storeys, six bays, straight-headed windows, and two doorways with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s and cornices on [[corbel|consoles]], one of which is blocked.  At the north end is a [[gable]] with kneelers, and in the gable is a [[Venetian window]].{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=316|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1227399|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Gatehouse, Castle Carr<br/><small>{{coord|53.76729|-1.96936|type:landmark|name=Gatehouse, Castle Carr}}</small>\n|[[File:Ruins, Castle Carr - geograph.org.uk - 19877.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1860\n|The [[gatehouse]] to Castle Carr, now demolished, is a ruin in stone and without a roof.  The gatehouse has three storeys, and contains an arched gateway containing a [[cast iron]] [[portcullis]] and oak gates with [[wrought iron]] grills.  There is an [[embattled]] [[parapet]] with false [[machicolation]]s, [[arrow slit]]s, clasping [[buttress]]es, and a [[mullion]]ed window.  In the corner is a stair tower, and at the rear are more archways, an [[oriel window]] containing a [[cross window]] with [[cant (architecture)|canted]] sides on dated [[corbel]]s, above which is a heraldic shield.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227430|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Barn east of Wilcroft House<br/><small>{{coord|53.76306|-2.00719|type:landmark|name=Barn east of Wilcroft House}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1861\n|A stone barn with a stone slate roof.  On the front is an elliptical-arched cart entry with [[rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] [[voussoir]]s, above it is a small window with a dated [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]], to the right is a doorway with sill-tie [[jamb]]s and a small window, and there are two [[lunette]]s with [[keystone (architecture)|keystones]].  In the left [[gable]] end is an owl hole, and at the rear are [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], a segmental-arched cart entry and two doorways, all with [[chamfer]]ed surrounds.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227392|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Low Lodge, Castle Carr<br/><small>{{coord|53.75859|-1.96774|type:landmark|name=Low Lodge, Castle Carr}}</small>\n|[[File:Castle Carr Gatehouse (4040916594).jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1868|c. 1868}}\n|This consists of a pair of stone lodges joined by an archway.  Each lodge has two storeys with [[mullion]]ed windows, an [[embattled]] [[parapet]] with stepped crenellation carried on false [[machicolation]], a [[Tudor arch]]ed doorway with sunken [[spandrel]]s, a tall stair tower with [[arrow slit]]s, and a single-storey [[bay (architecture)|bay]] at the rear.  Between the lodges is a semicircular archway with zig-zag ornament, on colonnettes, a [[hood mould]], and stepped crenellation surmounted by a large [[finial]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1227151|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Former Sunday School<br/><small>{{coord|53.76295|-2.00552|type:landmark|name=Former Sunday School}}</small>\n|[[File:Former Sunday School, Picket Well.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1868\n|The former Sunday school is in stone with [[rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], an [[eaves]] band, and a stone slate roof.  There is one two storey at the front facing the road, and two at the rear.  The front is symmetrical with three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], and it has a triangular [[pediment]]ed [[gable]] with a plaque in the [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]], a central doorway with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s, a [[fanlight]], and a [[cornice]] on [[corbel|consoles]], and this is flanked by tall round-headed windows with [[architrave]]s and [[keystone (architecture)|keystones]].  Along the sides are five bays and segmental-headed windows.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=316|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1227146|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Ventilation shaft (east}<br/><small>{{coord|53.76027|-1.98184|type:landmark|name=Ventilation shaft (east}}}</small>\n|[[File:Ventilation Shaft, Dimmin Dale.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1875|1870s}}\n|The ventilation shaft is for an underground water conduit.  It is in stone with a [[plinth]] and a [[cornice]], it is circular, and about {{convert|10|ft}} high.  The shaft contains four openings with iron grills.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227709|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Ventilation shaft (west}<br/><small>{{coord|53.76070|-1.98838|type:landmark|name=Ventilation shaft (west}}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1875|1870s}}\n|The ventilation shaft is for an underground water conduit.  It is in stone with a [[plinth]] and a [[cornice]], it is circular, and about {{convert|10|ft}} high.  The shaft contains four openings with iron grills.{{sfnp|Historic England|1227398|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Wadsworth War Memorial<br/><small>{{coord|53.75974|-2.01360|type:landmark|name=Wadsworth War Memorial}}</small>\n|[[File:Smeakin Hill War Memorial (WWI and WWII) - geograph.org.uk - 1516634.jpg|60px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|1923\n|The war memorial is on the top of a hill, and is in [[sandstone]].  It is {{convert|12.5|m}} high, and consists of an [[obelisk]] on a stepped base, on a square [[pedestal]], all on a square stone base.  The south face of the pedestal is recessed, and contains four tablets with inscriptions and the names of those lost in the two World Wars.{{sfnp|Historic England|1464951|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{portal|Yorkshire}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1227651|desc= Greenwood Stone, Wadsworth|access-date= 3 April 2020|mode=cs2}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1226935|desc= Akroyd Farmhouse and Akroyd Farm Cottage, Wadsworth|access-date= 2 April 2020|mod